12s5.388 12 12 12 12-5.38 12-12c0-6.612-5.38-12-12-12z" transform=""></path><path d="M 12 0C5.388 0 0 5.388 0 12s5.388 12 12 12 12-5.38 12-12c0-6.612-5.38-12-12-12z" transform="translate(26 0)"></path><path d="M 12 0C5.388 0 0 5.388 0 12s5.388 12 12 12 12-5.38 12-12c0-6.612-5.38-12-12-12z" transform="translate(52 0)"></path><path d="M 12 0C5.388 0 0 5.388 0 12s5.388 12 12 12 12-5.38 12-12c0-6.612-5.38-12-12-12z" transform="translate(78 0)"></path><path d="M 12 0C5.388 0 0 5.388 0 12s5.388 12 12 12 12-5.38 12-12c0-6.612-5.38-12-12-12zm0 2a9.983 9.983 0 019.995 10 10 10 0 01-10 10A10 10 0 012 12 10 10 0 0112 2z" transform="translate(104 0)"></path></svg></div><div class="biGQs _P fiohW qWPrE ncFvv fOtGX"><a target="_blank" tabindex="0" href="/ShowUserReviews-g304551-d311617-r751249521-Hazrat_Nizamuddin_Darga-New_Delhi_National_Capital_Territory_of_Delhi.html" class="BMQDV _F G- wSSLS SwZTJ FGwzt ukgoS"><span class="yCeTE">After the Great Mosque, the most evocative Islamic place of worship in Delhi.</span></a></div><div class="_T FKffI bmUTE"><div class="fIrGe _T bgMZj" style="-webkit-line-clamp:7;line-break:normal;cursor:pointer"><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB KxBGd"><span class="yCeTE">We learned from our guidebook that this complex, not far from the Humayun mausoleum, was worth visiting. So, after the visit to that mausoleum, we got transported to it by a motorickshaw.<br>This is a high place for Muslim worship in present-day India.<br>Dargah means mausoleum. Nizamuddin (full name: Khwaja Nizamuddin Auliya, 1238-1325) is a Sufi saint, belonging to the " Chishti" order. The order originated in present-day Afghanistan and is one of the four main orders of the sect of Sufi mystical "monks". Within the Chishti order, I learned that Nizamuddin is the founder of a particular branch, called precisely "Chishti Nizami". <br>The surrounding neighborhood was named after him, and also the nearby Hazrat Nizamuddin station, which is today one of the three main railway stations in Delhi.<br>Here the Nizamuddin shrine stands (which, however, is much later than him; as far as I read it dates back to 1562), together with other buildings, which host other shrines, shops related to his cult, and also a small baoli (stepwell).<br>To get to the mausoleum, from the spot of Lodhi Road where our motorickshaw left us, we walked a narrow, picturesque and crowded pedestrian street, lined with shops of all kinds. These shops are evidently favored by the continuous influx of shrine worshippers. After passing through an entrance arch, the shops also continue inside, further narrow and winding. Finally, after skirting the baoli, you reach the very crowded area where the shrine stands, under a large, highly decorated marble canopy surmounted by an onion-shaped dome.<br>No less evocative are other shrines that flank the courtyard where the main one stands.<br>Behind an offer, we received our tray of rose petals, with which to sprinkle the shrine.<br>The whole is extremely picturesque. And it certainly would have been even more so, if we had stayed until sunset, when, apparently, the Sufis sing poignant religious hymns. But it was not in our program to dwell so much.<br>As far as we could understand, after the Great Mosque this is the most evocative Islamic place of worship in Delhi.</span></div></div><div class="lszDU"><button class="UikNM _G B- _S _T c G_ P0 wSSLS wnNQG" type="button"><span class="biGQs _P XWJSj Wb">Read more</span><div class="CECjK"><svg viewBox="0 0 25 24" width="20px" height="20px" class="d Vb UmNoP"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M5.188 7.521l6.836 6.837 6.837-6.837 1.06 1.06-7.366 7.368a.75.75 0 01-1.061 0L4.127 8.582l1.06-1.06z"></path></svg></div></button></div></div><div></div><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB xUqsL mowmC KxBGd"><a target="_blank" tabindex="0" href="/Attraction_Review-g304551-d311617-Reviews-Hazrat_Nizamuddin_Darga-New_Delhi_National_Capital_Territory_of_Delhi.html#REVIEWS" class="BMQDV _F G- wSSLS SwZTJ FGwzt suezE">Review of: Hazrat Nizamuddin Darga</a></div><div class="TreSq"><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB ncFvv osNWb">Written 17 March 2020</div><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB mowmC osNWb">This review is the subjective opinion of a Tripadvisor member and not of Tripadvisor LLC. class="yCeTE">History in a wilderness</span></a></div><div class="_T FKffI bmUTE"><div class="fIrGe _T bgMZj" style="-webkit-line-clamp:7;line-break:normal;cursor:pointer"><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB KxBGd"><span class="yCeTE">This vast green space in Mehrauli, very close to the Qutb Minar (which you can see from the park) is home to some very interesting and important historical monuments. These include the medieval step-well known as Rajon ki Baoli; several unidentified tombs; an interesting horse stable; the tomb of the Sultanate era ruler, Balban; the mosque and tomb of Jamaali-Kamaali, which dates back to Humayuns era; and the tomb of Mohammad Quli Khan, refurbished and added to by Thomas Metcalfe to create a holiday home. There are other historical structures, from lone walls to domed pavilions (Metcalfes follies) and a boathouse that was originally a dovecote. <br><br>Recent changes mean that there are now several manicured lawns, hedges, benches and even a couple of outdoor gyms added alongside some of the paths around Jamaali-Kamaali and Quli Khans Tomb. The area leading from there to Rajon ki Baoli, however, is more wild, with relatively untouched trees and dirt paths. <br><br>No entry fee is charged. The park is open between sunrise and sunset.</span></div></div><div class="lszDU"><button class="UikNM _G B- _S _T c G_ P0 wSSLS wnNQG" type="button"><span class="biGQs _P XWJSj Wb">Read more</span><div class="CECjK"><svg viewBox="0 0 25 24" width="20px" height="20px" class="d Vb UmNoP"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M5.188 7.521l6.836 6.837 6.837-6.837 1.06 1.06-7.366 7.368a.75.75 0 01-1.061 0L4.127 8.582l1.06-1.06z"></path></svg></div></button></div></div><div></div><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB xUqsL mowmC KxBGd"><a target="_blank" tabindex="0" href="/Attraction_Review-g304551-d3971182-Reviews-Mehrauli_Archaeological_Park-New_Delhi_National_Capital_Territory_of_Delhi.html#REVIEWS" class="BMQDV _F G- wSSLS SwZTJ FGwzt suezE">Review of: Mehrauli Archaeological Park</a></div><div class="TreSq"><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB ncFvv osNWb">Written 1 December 2022</div><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB mowmC osNWb">This review is the subjective opinion of a Tripadvisor member and not of Tripadvisor LLC.
